@node "Intro" "ZAPP Introduction"
             ___     _               _         _   _
            |_ _|_ _| |_ _ _ ___  __| |_  _ __| |_(_)___ _ _
             | || ' \  _| '_/ _ \/ _` | || / _|  _| / _ \ ' \
            |___|_||_\__|_| \___/\__,_|\_,_\__|\__|_\___/_||_|

                                    or

                        What is this thing anyhow?

   You've just called your favourite BBS and spent five minutes scanning
through the file lists picking out a few choice items which you've now
started to download.  Watching a couple of megs of data download may be
some peoples idea of a good time or perhaps you wander off and make a cup
of tea while ZModem does its magic.  Ten minutes later the transfer has
finished and you log off leaving the SysOp pretty bored, the rest of the
BBS untouched and the phone company a little richer...

   Sound familiar?  Ok, here's the ZAPP version:

   You call the BBS and are greeted by some sampled music as you logon.
More samples play as you progress through the latest news and bulletins
till you get to the file menu.  You spend five minutes listing and
selecting files which you then start to download.  Instead of a transfer
window coming up you are put straight back into the file menu!  There isn't
a problem: the files are being transfered in the background!  At this point
you can go and play some online games, read/write some messages, chat to
the SysOp or even start an upload safe in the knowledge that the files you
selected are being stored in your download directory!  The download
finishes and you log off leaving the SysOp happy, the highest score in the
'ANSI Death By Jelly' game, and the phone company a little richer...  (ZAPP
cannot fix that last one :)

   Before we go any further, here are a few general questions and their
answers:

 Q: Do I need to use a custom terminal?  I hate those...
 A: I don't like those either so ZAPP works with any existing terminal
    program like NComm, Term, whatever...

 Q: Is it difficult to @{"install" Link "Install"}?
 A: Not at all!  Just run the included installer script and tell your
    terminal program to use the zapp.device instead of the usual
    serial.device (or whatever serial device you use).  Thats it!

 Q: Can I use it on every BBS I call?
 A: Fraid not!  Only @{"Zeus BBS" Link "Zeus"}' have the power to run as a ZAPP server.

 Q: Can I tell my BBS package to use zapp.device and make it ZAPP capable?
 A: No, since zapp.device is for clients only.

 Q: How does it work?
 A: Its magic!  And its a secret so if I told you it wouldn't be a secret
    anymore and that's no fun!!

 Q: Ok, this sounds kind of interesting.  How much does it cost?
 A: Put your wallet away!  The ZAPP user archive is totally FREE!  Isn't it
    just a lovely day =o]

   If you've not already raced off to install ZAPP then here is a brief
feature list with some nice jargon you can use to impress your friends and
family:

 - Easy to install.

 - Works with any terminal program.

 - Reliable asynchronous server<->client packet system.

 - Full packet routing capabilities.

 - Can optionally use XPK compression.

 - GUI configuration program.

   And here is a brief description of the ZAPP clients supplied in this
distribution:

 - @{"SMSG" Link "SMSG"} : Opens up a simple requester on your terminal screen.

 - @{"XFER" Link "XFER"} : Bi-Directional file transfers.

 - @{"ZPCM" Link "ZPCM"} : Plays PCM samples in real-time.

 - @{"ZNFS" Link "ZNFS"} : ZAPP Network File System.

 - See @{"The Future..." Link "Future"} for a list of planned clients.

@endnode

@node "Install" "ZAPP Installation"
               ___         _        _ _      _   _          
              |_ _|_ _  __| |_ __ _| | |__ _| |_(_)___ _ _  
               | || ' \(_-<  _/ _` | | / _` |  _| / _ \ ' \ 
              |___|_||_/__/\__\__,_|_|_\__,_|\__|_\___/_||_|

   Please use the supplied installer script to install ZAPP.  It sets up
the default configuration as well as all the path information the system
will need to run ZAPP correctly.  Just double click on the 'ZappInstall'
icon and follow the instructions.  Help is available during the
installation so please use it if you are not clear what the installer is
doing!

   Once the installer has finished you'll need to tell your terminal
program to use ZAPP.  All this involves is loading your terminal and
telling it to use zapp.device instead of your normal serial device.

   NOTE: The installer puts zapp.device into the ZAPP/Devs directory
instead of just copying it to DEVS:  This is to help keep all ZAPP related
files in one directory instead of spreading them all over your hard
disk(s).

   The only other thing you need to do is check that your terminal will
hangup by dropping DTR.  Sending the +++ATH modem command will not work
when ZAPP mode is active.

   Thats all there is to it!!

@endnode

@node "Config" "ZAPP Configuration"
            ___           __ _                    _   _          
           / __|___ _ _  / _(_)__ _ _  _ _ _ __ _| |_(_)___ _ _  
          | (__/ _ \ ' \|  _| / _` | || | '_/ _` |  _| / _ \ ' \ 
           \___\___/_||_|_| |_\__, |\_,_|_| \__,_|\__|_\___/_||_|
                              |___/                              

   Although the installation process setup a default configuration, there is
a GUI config program to setup all the other options for the zapp.device.
This section describes the GUI window and how to configure ZAPP via its
environment variables.

   In the ZAPP directory you will find a program called 'ZappPrefs' which
is, although the name wouldn't give you any clues, the ZAPP GUI
configuration program.  When double clicked a window appears with the
following sections and gadgets:

                               Serial Device
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This section defines which serial device should be used.  On its own,
zapp.device won't be able to talk to your modem since it doesn't have any
hardware serial routines in it: it sits between your terminal program and
your serial device and 'siphons' off the ZAPP information so the terminal
*thinks* its using a normal device!

   Device : This is the name of the REAL serial device ZAPP will use.  ZAPP
            has been tested with serial.device, artser.device, 8n1.device
            and ibmser.device.
            
            Clicking on the small disk icon next to the Device string
            gadget will bring up a file requester to select the device
            with.

   Unit   : This is the unit of the REAL serial device ZAPP will use.  This
            is usually zero unless you have a multi-port serial card.

   Shared : ZAPP will normally open the REAL serial device in exclusive
            mode so no other programs can interfere with the data flow.  If
            you should need it to open in shared mode then select this
            checkbox.

   7 Wire : If your modem does data compression then you probably have a
            seven-wire modem cable so the system can detect the RTS/CTS
            signals from the modem.  This should generally be checked
            unless you are using ZAPP with some old 300-1200 baud modem!

                                  Screen
                                 ~~~~~~~~
   ZAPP clients can open their own windows and it is desirable for them to
open on your terminal screen.  This section allows you to specify which
screen ZAPP should use.  This also affects where the ZAPP status window
will appear (more on that in the @{"Usage" Link "Usage"} section).

   Type : Specifies the type of screen you want ZAPP to use.  This is
          useful for some old terminal programs that don't open a public
          screen.  The options are:

             Default - The default public screen - usually Workbench.

             Front   - The front most screen.
             
             Active  - The active screen.
             
             Public  - A named public screen.  This option will enable the
                       Name gadget.
   
   Name : The name of the public screen you want ZAPP to use.  Note: public
          screen names are case sensitive.

                                 Commodity
                                ~~~~~~~~~~~
   ZAPP has a status window showing all the currently active clients.  This
section defines how the window is opened.

   PopKey : Specifies the key combination that will bring up the ZAPP
            status window.  Usually set to 'ctrl lshift <unit number>'.
   
   PopUp  : If this gadget is checked, the ZAPP status window will appear
            as soon as a ZAPP connection is made to a BBS.

   Pri    : The priority of the commodity.  Defaults to zero and should be
            left that way unless you have a reason to change it!

                              XPK Compression
                             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   To increase the bandwidth capability, ZAPP can use the XPK compression
library system to compress packets before transmission.  If you do not have
XPK installed then this section of gadgets will all be ghosted and not
available for use.

   Type : ZappPrefs will perform a scan to see what XPK libraries you have
          installed and filter out any which cannot be used by ZAPP.  This
          cycle gadget contains all the compression types that you can use.

   Mode : Sets the compression mode.  Zero is generally very poor but fast
          compression and 100 is good compression but slow speed.  The
          number to the right of the slider shows the current mode.

   ?    : Brings up an information requester showing details about the
          selected compression type and mode.

                              ZAPP Directory
                             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This is the directory that ZAPP has been installed into and is setup
automatically by the installation process.  The disk icon to the right will
bring up a directory requester.

                            Download Directory
                            ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This is the directory that files will be downloaded to when you download
files on the BBS using ZAPP's own multi-tasking transfer protocols.  This
should be the same place your terminal normally puts downloaded files!

                              ZappPrefs Menus
                             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   You can define multiple zapp.device units each having completely
different preference settings.  The configuration information for each unit
is stored in the ENV:ZAPP/ directory and called ZappDevice.<unit>  The
ZappPrefs menu allows you to load and save the settings for any unit by
selecting the relevant file.

   Open       :  Opens an old ZappDevice.<unit> settings file.  If the
                 current configuration has changed, a requester will appear
                 asking whether you want to Save or Discard the changes or
                 cancel the operation.

   Save       : Saves the current configuration.

   Save As... : Brings up a file requester allowing you to specify the
                filename that the current settings should be saved under.

   Quit       : Quits ZappPrefs.  If the current configuration has changed,
                a requester will appear asking whether you want to Save or
                Discard the changes or cancel the operation.

@endnode

