@node "Connect" "Connecting to a ZAPP system"

   So you've installed ZAPP, run the configuration program and got bored
with that, loaded your terminal and told it to use zapp.device, set DTR
hangup and now you want to see ZAPP in action.  Not surprising!!  Ok, now
you'll need the phone number of a system running Zeus BBS.  There are quite
a few of these around and although they may not actually say they run Zeus,
you can see if they're ZAPP compatible by watching for the following string
during logon:

[Example logon sequence using a normal serial.device]

ATDT...

CONNECT 28800/ARQ

Welcome to the BBS...

Press [ESCAPE] twice...

ANSI Terminal Detected
żZAPP?

You have connected to ....

[End of example]

   Just under the ANSI detection message you can see the 'żZAPP?' string.
This is sent from the BBS to get the zapp.device to enter into ZAPP mode
and if you see it while logging onto a BBS, you know it supports the ZAPP
protocol.

   When calling a ZAPP capable BBS with the zapp.device, you should see
this instead:

[Example logon sequence using the zapp.device]

ATDT...

CONNECT 28800/ARQ

Welcome to the BBS...

Press [ESCAPE] twice...

ANSI Terminal Detected
ZAPP Terminal Detected

You have connected to ....

[End of example]

   If all went well, zapp.device responded to the ZAPP initialisation
string and the BBS has sent the 'ZAPP Terminal Detected' message to let you
know about it.

   At this point the ZAPP status window will popup if you have told it to
in ZappPrefs by setting the 'PopUp' checkbox in the commodity section.

   As you will see, the flow of text from the BBS acts completely as
normal since the terminal still thinks its talking to a REAL serial device.
You may notice slight response delays while using the BBS but this is
normal and is due to the protocol overhead that is incured when clients are
running.

                          The ZAPP Status Window
                         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   ZAPP clients generally run in the background and do not have any kind of
status window of their own.  Instead they connect to the ZAPP status window
and have a one line entry to show what they're up to.

   The format of each entry is:

      PROT/X: Status...

   Where 'PROT' is the four-letter ZAPP protocol ID (See the client
descriptions for examples) and 'X' is the client ID.  You can run several
copies of the same client at the same time and each one will have the same
protocol ID but a different client ID number.

   IMPORTANT NOTE: To stop a client that is running in the background,
click on its entry in the ZAPP status window while holding down either one
of the shift keys.

   The status window itself has information about your dynamic ZAPP address
in the title bar as well as the ZAPP address of your host.  You only need
to know this for @{"power usage" Link "Power"} of the ZAPP clients.

   Clicking the close gadget on the status window will not quit ZAPP, it
will just hide the window.  You can bring the window back up with the
PopKey combination you specified in ZappPrefs.  For the default
installation, you need to press CTRL, the left SHIFT key and 0 all at the
same time.

@endnode

@node "SMSG" "ZAPP Simple Message Protocol"

   Protocol Name: ZAPP Simple Message Protocol

     Protocol ID: SMSG

     Description: Brings up a simple requester on your terminal screen
                  with one or more options and will wait until you have
                  selected one.

   This was the first client that was written for ZAPP and as the name
suggests, it is fairly basic.  I've included it though because it can be
quite useful for very noticable system messages or for allowing the user to
choose from several options.

@endnode

@node "XFER" "ZAPP File Transfer Protocol"

   Protocol Name: ZAPP File Transfer Protocol

     Protocol ID: RECV - When receiving files
     Protocol ID: SEND - When sending files

     Description: Transfers one or more files between you and the host
                  system.

   These were also early clients which simply transfer files.  They will
attempt to resume a transfer if they find a file with the same name and
date as the original.

@endnode

@node "ZPCM" "ZAPP Real-Time PCM Samples"

   Protocol Name: ZAPP Real-Time PCM Sample Player

     Protocol ID: ZPCM

     Description: Transfers and plays a PCM compressed 8-Bit sample.

   BBS' have always had very limited sound capabilities mostly consisting
of single beeps although there is an ANSI extension to allow single channel
'music' to be played to the user.

   ZPCM however transfers binary PCM encoded 8-Bit samples and plays them
as they are received.  The sound quality isn't brilliant since PCM
compression actually 'looses' some of the audio data causing distortion.

   Another limitation is due to bandwidth: even with PCM compression the
sample needs to be at around 8khz to be played over a 28800 baud link
without breaking up.  (CD's usually play at about 44khz)

   Despite these limitations, PCM samples can be a lot of fun and, once you
get used to the quality, quite enjoyable =o)

@endnode

@node "ZNFS" "ZAPP Network File System"

   Protocol Name: ZAPP Network File System

     Protocol ID: ZNFS
     
     Description: Mounts a device from the host system to the users system
                  causing it to appear on the users workbench/device list.

   This is a fun one!  The host system can mount devices on your machine.
For example, an icon appears on your Workbench called 'FileBase' which is
the entire file base of the BBS you are calling.  This can be now be
accessed via icons or Shell or even directory tools like DirOpus.

   There is no limit to the amount of devices the host can mount so you may
get a filebase icon and maybe a couple of CD-Roms depending on what system
you call!  As far as AmigaDOS/Workbench are concerned, these are REAL file
systems that have just magically appeared and will act as such.  I.e. you
can actually run programs that are stored on the host system (the program
will run on your machine of course), list archives, view pictures, or copy
files onto your hard disk, just like a normal device!

   IMPORTANT NOTE: Before you logoff be sure to close all windows,
applications and anything else that references the ZAPP devices.  Failure
to do so may result in system instability.

   Currently ZNFS is read-only.  This will change in the future to allow
uploads to the BBS and other fun stuff.

   One nice side effect of ZNFS is that the host system can setup WWW pages
which you can access using any web browser!  For example, the host mounts a
device called ZAPP: which contains a file called index.html.  Just run your
web program and tell it to load:

      http://localhost/zapp:index.html

   Worra laugh =oD

@endnode

